

1
00:00:00.506 --> 00:00:10.596 A:middle
[ Silence ]

2
00:00:11.096 --> 00:00:13.286 A:middle
&gt;&gt; My name is Troy
and I'm an engineer

3
00:00:13.286 --> 00:00:15.096 A:middle
on the debugger UI
team for Xcode.

4
00:00:15.746 --> 00:00:18.066 A:middle
And I'm glad to see so
many people here today

5
00:00:18.066 --> 00:00:20.736 A:middle
because we all know that
debugging is really important.

6
00:00:21.376 --> 00:00:24.756 A:middle
And you know that debugging
is what sets your app apart

7
00:00:24.756 --> 00:00:26.836 A:middle
from the app on the App
Store that gets one star

8
00:00:26.986 --> 00:00:28.496 A:middle
because it crashes on launch.

9
00:00:29.336 --> 00:00:32.286 A:middle
And debugging is what sets
your app apart from the app

10
00:00:32.286 --> 00:00:35.936 A:middle
on our iOS devices that use all
the memory and evict other apps

11
00:00:36.286 --> 00:00:38.596 A:middle
when our users are trying
to do some multitasking.

12
00:00:39.066 --> 00:00:42.056 A:middle
And debugging is what sets
your app apart from the apps

13
00:00:42.316 --> 00:00:45.306 A:middle
on our Mac and iOS portables
that use all of battery life

14
00:00:45.636 --> 00:00:48.776 A:middle
in just a few hours making it a
worst experience for everyone.

15
00:00:49.286 --> 00:00:51.686 A:middle
But you guys know that already.

16
00:00:52.976 --> 00:00:54.886 A:middle
You're here because
debugging is hard.

17
00:00:55.116 --> 00:00:58.586 A:middle
I like this quote from
Brian Kernighan and it says,

18
00:00:58.586 --> 00:01:00.906 A:middle
"Everybody knows that
debugging is twice as hard

19
00:01:01.256 --> 00:01:02.816 A:middle
as writing a program
in the first place.

20
00:01:03.446 --> 00:01:06.196 A:middle
So if you're as clever as you
can be when you're writing it

21
00:01:06.246 --> 00:01:09.226 A:middle
in the first place, how are
you ever going to debug it?"

22
00:01:10.116 --> 00:01:13.106 A:middle
Well, the answer is better
tools and specifically,

23
00:01:14.096 --> 00:01:16.216 A:middle
the new debugging
tools in Xcode 5.

24
00:01:16.836 --> 00:01:20.186 A:middle
We have a lot of new
things to cover today.

25
00:01:20.706 --> 00:01:22.636 A:middle
But first, let's go
on a tour of the UI

26
00:01:22.966 --> 00:01:25.236 A:middle
so we have a common
vocabulary when we know--

27
00:01:25.236 --> 00:01:26.436 A:middle
when we're talking
about these things.

28
00:01:27.486 --> 00:01:30.546 A:middle
So here is the brand
new, Xcode 5 UI.

29
00:01:31.366 --> 00:01:32.286 A:middle
And the first thing you're going

30
00:01:32.286 --> 00:01:35.276 A:middle
to notice is we've moved the
breakpoints activation button

31
00:01:35.466 --> 00:01:39.606 A:middle
from the toolbar down
into the debug bar

32
00:01:40.616 --> 00:01:42.966 A:middle
because it's right there next
to the other tools that you need

33
00:01:42.966 --> 00:01:45.946 A:middle
when you're debugging such as
Continue, Step Over, Step Into.

34
00:01:46.026 --> 00:01:48.476 A:middle
And it's just a much
more natural place

35
00:01:48.946 --> 00:01:51.806 A:middle
to disable all your breakpoints
if you need to do that

36
00:01:51.806 --> 00:01:52.686 A:middle
and then hit Continue.

37
00:01:53.866 --> 00:01:57.816 A:middle
If you need to enable or
disable breakpoints one by one,

38
00:01:57.816 --> 00:02:00.096 A:middle
of course, we go to the
breakpoints navigator.

39
00:02:00.096 --> 00:02:06.616 A:middle
And here you see a list of all
of the breakpoints separated

40
00:02:06.616 --> 00:02:08.946 A:middle
by filename and line number.

41
00:02:09.576 --> 00:02:13.556 A:middle
And you can edit or disable,
enable breakpoints right here.

42
00:02:14.406 --> 00:02:18.446 A:middle
But not all breakpoints have
filenames and file numbers.

43
00:02:19.426 --> 00:02:20.966 A:middle
There are some special
breakpoints.

44
00:02:22.086 --> 00:02:26.706 A:middle
And we create those down
at the bottom of the window

45
00:02:26.736 --> 00:02:28.716 A:middle
where you can create
symbolic breakpoints

46
00:02:28.716 --> 00:02:29.976 A:middle
or the exception breakpoints

47
00:02:30.396 --> 00:02:32.736 A:middle
that are more special
breakpoints.

48
00:02:33.216 --> 00:02:35.296 A:middle
And we got a two new
breakpoint types that are

49
00:02:35.296 --> 00:02:36.526 A:middle
like the exception breakpoints.

50
00:02:37.306 --> 00:02:40.986 A:middle
And that's the OpenGL
ES error breakpoint

51
00:02:41.416 --> 00:02:43.136 A:middle
and the unit test
failure breakpoint.

52
00:02:44.226 --> 00:02:45.356 A:middle
Both of these breakpoints
are kind

53
00:02:45.356 --> 00:02:46.866 A:middle
of like the exception
breakpoints

54
00:02:47.046 --> 00:02:48.826 A:middle
where you can set it once
and just kind of forget

55
00:02:48.826 --> 00:02:49.766 A:middle
about it in your project.

56
00:02:49.846 --> 00:02:53.456 A:middle
And then when you have an
error, Xcode is going to pause

57
00:02:53.456 --> 00:02:55.586 A:middle
in your applications
code instead

58
00:02:55.586 --> 00:02:58.466 A:middle
of some error handler later on.

59
00:02:58.636 --> 00:03:02.146 A:middle
So that's a really great way to
catch those errors in unit tests

60
00:03:02.146 --> 00:03:06.286 A:middle
and in your OpenGL
ES games on iOS.

61
00:03:06.716 --> 00:03:12.466 A:middle
Let's move on to the-- there's
another navigator that's really

62
00:03:12.466 --> 00:03:15.256 A:middle
important of course and
that's the debug navigator.

63
00:03:15.836 --> 00:03:18.686 A:middle
And the first thing
you're going to notice

64
00:03:18.686 --> 00:03:23.006 A:middle
in the debug navigator is
this brand new debug gauges.

65
00:03:23.216 --> 00:03:24.696 A:middle
And we're going to talk
a lot about that later.

66
00:03:24.696 --> 00:03:26.026 A:middle
So let's skip it for now.

67
00:03:26.626 --> 00:03:30.366 A:middle
I do want to draw your
attention to this icon here.

68
00:03:30.366 --> 00:03:32.656 A:middle
This is the spool of
thread icon and this means

69
00:03:32.656 --> 00:03:36.936 A:middle
that your debug navigator
is in threads mode.

70
00:03:36.936 --> 00:03:40.216 A:middle
And so, down here, you
get a list of your threads

71
00:03:40.886 --> 00:03:42.866 A:middle
and a stack trace where
you're paused in the debugger.

72
00:03:42.866 --> 00:03:46.096 A:middle
And this is a really great
place 'cause you can navigate

73
00:03:46.096 --> 00:03:49.106 A:middle
through that stack trace and
jump through the files that led

74
00:03:49.106 --> 00:03:52.226 A:middle
up to where you are in your
paused application code.

75
00:03:53.086 --> 00:03:56.066 A:middle
And you can even check out
the parameters that went

76
00:03:56.066 --> 00:03:58.136 A:middle
into the calculations that
got you to this point.

77
00:03:58.646 --> 00:04:01.306 A:middle
And so, you can figure out
why you got to this point

78
00:04:01.306 --> 00:04:03.866 A:middle
and why maybe you need
to go somewhere else.

79
00:04:04.976 --> 00:04:07.266 A:middle
But let's return back to
that spool of thread icon

80
00:04:07.266 --> 00:04:09.366 A:middle
because you can change that and
a lot of people don't know that.

81
00:04:10.046 --> 00:04:13.976 A:middle
If you're using grand central
dispatch, it's more natural

82
00:04:13.976 --> 00:04:16.555 A:middle
to organize your threads by cue.

83
00:04:17.226 --> 00:04:19.546 A:middle
And so, this is exactly
what this spool--

84
00:04:19.546 --> 00:04:23.286 A:middle
this grand central dispatch
stoplight icon indicates

85
00:04:23.286 --> 00:04:25.006 A:middle
that we're grouping
your threads by cue.

86
00:04:26.646 --> 00:04:30.326 A:middle
Now, let's move on to
the variables view.

87
00:04:32.876 --> 00:04:37.066 A:middle
The variables view is where when
you stopped at a breakpoint,

88
00:04:37.066 --> 00:04:39.736 A:middle
it will show you the
most important variables

89
00:04:40.226 --> 00:04:43.016 A:middle
for that line of code and
that might be local variables,

90
00:04:43.096 --> 00:04:47.116 A:middle
it might be instance variables
or parameters to the method

91
00:04:47.116 --> 00:04:48.876 A:middle
and Xcode does a
really great job

92
00:04:48.876 --> 00:04:50.596 A:middle
of choosing those
variables for you.

93
00:04:51.206 --> 00:04:53.676 A:middle
But in some situations,
you need to find

94
00:04:53.676 --> 00:04:55.146 A:middle
out a little bit
more information.

95
00:04:55.706 --> 00:04:58.236 A:middle
Maybe, you need to find out
a global variable state,

96
00:04:58.236 --> 00:05:00.486 A:middle
or you need to find out
some register states.

97
00:05:01.156 --> 00:05:09.406 A:middle
And so, you can click on this
toggle down here and change auto

98
00:05:09.536 --> 00:05:13.146 A:middle
to all and that will give
you a more expansive view

99
00:05:13.146 --> 00:05:13.976 A:middle
of your variables.

100
00:05:14.506 --> 00:05:20.436 A:middle
Let's move on to
the debug console.

101
00:05:21.896 --> 00:05:25.746 A:middle
The debug console is where
you receive the output

102
00:05:25.746 --> 00:05:28.416 A:middle
from your application whether
that's NSLogs, printfs,

103
00:05:28.696 --> 00:05:30.016 A:middle
or maybe the system frameworks

104
00:05:30.016 --> 00:05:32.436 A:middle
that you're using are showing
you some warnings or errors

105
00:05:32.436 --> 00:05:34.116 A:middle
that you need to be aware
of and they're going

106
00:05:34.116 --> 00:05:35.296 A:middle
to come out right here.

107
00:05:36.226 --> 00:05:38.526 A:middle
Of course, when you're paused
in the debugger, this is also

108
00:05:38.616 --> 00:05:42.056 A:middle
where you have a direct
conduit to the LLDB debugger

109
00:05:42.586 --> 00:05:44.846 A:middle
which is a state of the art
debugger that powers so many

110
00:05:44.846 --> 00:05:46.806 A:middle
of the features in Xcode,
and we're going to talk more

111
00:05:46.806 --> 00:05:48.416 A:middle
about that and how
it's integrated

112
00:05:48.416 --> 00:05:50.076 A:middle
with Xcode more a little later.

113
00:05:50.826 --> 00:05:53.526 A:middle
And so, that's basically
the main aspects

114
00:05:53.566 --> 00:05:55.286 A:middle
of the debugging in Xcode.

115
00:05:55.596 --> 00:05:57.846 A:middle
And of course, we've added new
things which we're going to talk

116
00:05:57.846 --> 00:06:01.346 A:middle
about today including
the new debugging gauges

117
00:06:01.496 --> 00:06:03.746 A:middle
which we saw briefly.

118
00:06:04.666 --> 00:06:08.856 A:middle
We're going to see a new way to
debug, a new debugging workflow.

119
00:06:09.056 --> 00:06:11.836 A:middle
And then we're going to look at
a specific debugging workflow

120
00:06:12.096 --> 00:06:14.296 A:middle
which is really great
now with XPC services.

121
00:06:14.876 --> 00:06:18.326 A:middle
So let's talk about performance.

122
00:06:19.196 --> 00:06:21.466 A:middle
We all know that performance
is extremely important.

123
00:06:21.466 --> 00:06:23.546 A:middle
Nobody likes to see stutters
in their application.

124
00:06:23.986 --> 00:06:26.456 A:middle
Nobody wants to see scrolling
stuff for any reason.

125
00:06:28.426 --> 00:06:32.096 A:middle
But you've ever hung on
the Apple developer forums,

126
00:06:32.096 --> 00:06:34.486 A:middle
you may have heard,
"Don't pre-optimize."

127
00:06:35.456 --> 00:06:38.206 A:middle
And you may even get this quote
from Donald Knuth that says,

128
00:06:38.796 --> 00:06:42.206 A:middle
"Essentially, pre-optimization
is the root of all evil."

129
00:06:42.846 --> 00:06:45.926 A:middle
I think we can agree

130
00:06:45.926 --> 00:06:47.666 A:middle
that there's a little
bit of hyperbole here.

131
00:06:48.186 --> 00:06:50.776 A:middle
But we can also agree
that if you think

132
00:06:50.776 --> 00:06:53.106 A:middle
about performance before you
think about code correctness,

133
00:06:53.106 --> 00:06:54.856 A:middle
you end up with code
that's harder to read,

134
00:06:55.196 --> 00:06:57.656 A:middle
code that's harder to
maintain, and ultimately,

135
00:06:57.946 --> 00:07:00.446 A:middle
code that may not even be
correct in the first place.

136
00:07:00.446 --> 00:07:06.006 A:middle
So if performance is
such an important aspect

137
00:07:06.006 --> 00:07:08.486 A:middle
of your application, but we
don't want to pre-optimize

138
00:07:08.986 --> 00:07:10.986 A:middle
when are we supposed to
optimize our programs?

139
00:07:11.256 --> 00:07:14.866 A:middle
We should optimize when
we measure a problem.

140
00:07:16.056 --> 00:07:19.036 A:middle
This is the only time that
we know what's going wrong

141
00:07:19.036 --> 00:07:20.366 A:middle
so we can fix that instead

142
00:07:20.366 --> 00:07:21.846 A:middle
of what we think
might be going wrong.

143
00:07:22.416 --> 00:07:25.676 A:middle
And Instruments is
the best place to go

144
00:07:25.766 --> 00:07:26.856 A:middle
and optimize your code.

145
00:07:27.556 --> 00:07:30.706 A:middle
There are sessions this week and
there's videos from prior years

146
00:07:30.706 --> 00:07:32.166 A:middle
to tell you how to
use Instruments.

147
00:07:32.816 --> 00:07:37.166 A:middle
But the good news is now in
Xcode 5, Xcode is measuring

148
00:07:37.166 --> 00:07:40.526 A:middle
for you all of the time, and
that's the new debug gauges.

149
00:07:41.126 --> 00:07:45.426 A:middle
Debug gauges show up
in the debug navigator,

150
00:07:45.606 --> 00:07:47.006 A:middle
right there where you
can always see them.

151
00:07:47.006 --> 00:07:48.936 A:middle
And this is really
great a place for them

152
00:07:48.936 --> 00:07:50.586 A:middle
because when you just
pause, it switches to that.

153
00:07:51.146 --> 00:07:52.006 A:middle
It's right there, you just need

154
00:07:52.006 --> 00:07:54.846 A:middle
to peak behind your current
application or if you're

155
00:07:54.846 --> 00:07:58.016 A:middle
on a device, it's right
there on your Mac.

156
00:07:58.246 --> 00:08:00.586 A:middle
There's a bunch of
debugging gauges

157
00:08:00.586 --> 00:08:03.426 A:middle
to show you the performance
and the characteristics

158
00:08:03.426 --> 00:08:04.866 A:middle
of all sorts of technologies.

159
00:08:05.536 --> 00:08:08.146 A:middle
There are two debugging gauges

160
00:08:08.396 --> 00:08:10.536 A:middle
that are universal no matter
what kind of app you're writing,

161
00:08:10.536 --> 00:08:13.556 A:middle
what platform you're
targeting, and that's the CPU

162
00:08:13.656 --> 00:08:15.166 A:middle
and the memory debugging gauges.

163
00:08:16.066 --> 00:08:17.896 A:middle
And so, since those
are universal,

164
00:08:18.376 --> 00:08:21.446 A:middle
we're going to take a look
at them more closely today.

165
00:08:21.496 --> 00:08:25.536 A:middle
So first step, the CPU gauge.

166
00:08:26.116 --> 00:08:28.816 A:middle
We show you a chart
of the recent history

167
00:08:28.816 --> 00:08:32.775 A:middle
of a CPU utilization which
is your first indication

168
00:08:32.775 --> 00:08:34.716 A:middle
that something may be going
wrong in your application.

169
00:08:34.716 --> 00:08:36.666 A:middle
If you see a spike
that you didn't expect,

170
00:08:37.006 --> 00:08:39.756 A:middle
or if you see a pegged on a
processor and you don't know

171
00:08:39.756 --> 00:08:42.486 A:middle
that that's happening,
you want to take a look

172
00:08:42.486 --> 00:08:43.785 A:middle
at that, take a deeper look.

173
00:08:43.785 --> 00:08:48.026 A:middle
And to do that, you click on
the CPU gauge and it brings

174
00:08:48.026 --> 00:08:50.656 A:middle
up the beautiful CPU
debugging report.

175
00:08:50.656 --> 00:08:53.856 A:middle
Some of the characteristics
of these reports

176
00:08:53.856 --> 00:08:56.536 A:middle
that are common among all of the
reports, so let's take a look

177
00:08:56.536 --> 00:08:58.546 A:middle
through some of the aspects.

178
00:08:59.146 --> 00:09:01.886 A:middle
First we have this view here
which is the meter view.

179
00:09:02.696 --> 00:09:04.966 A:middle
The meter view shows you a
snapshot of what's happening

180
00:09:04.966 --> 00:09:09.236 A:middle
in your code right now in your
application to give you an idea

181
00:09:10.076 --> 00:09:11.266 A:middle
of what's going on right now.

182
00:09:11.876 --> 00:09:16.266 A:middle
As you can see here,
we're using 97 percent

183
00:09:16.386 --> 00:09:17.656 A:middle
of the CPU utilization.

184
00:09:18.416 --> 00:09:19.996 A:middle
And that puts the
needle about halfway

185
00:09:19.996 --> 00:09:25.056 A:middle
because this iOS device has
a two core processor and so,

186
00:09:25.056 --> 00:09:27.206 A:middle
it's out of a total
of 200 percent.

187
00:09:27.566 --> 00:09:30.206 A:middle
We don't know whether that's
50 percent of each core

188
00:09:30.206 --> 00:09:32.436 A:middle
and we don't know if that's
100 percent of 1 core,

189
00:09:32.436 --> 00:09:33.246 A:middle
and zero percent of the other.

190
00:09:33.246 --> 00:09:34.956 A:middle
But we know that approximately,

191
00:09:35.246 --> 00:09:38.356 A:middle
half the CPU utilization is
going to our application.

192
00:09:39.226 --> 00:09:40.526 A:middle
I also want to draw
your attention

193
00:09:40.526 --> 00:09:43.656 A:middle
to the small inner blue
arc because that's a range

194
00:09:43.656 --> 00:09:46.216 A:middle
of the last few minutes
of CPU utilization.

195
00:09:46.216 --> 00:09:49.266 A:middle
So you know whether things
have been wildly swinging back

196
00:09:49.266 --> 00:09:53.316 A:middle
and forth or if it's just
been pegged at a narrow range

197
00:09:53.316 --> 00:09:56.376 A:middle
such as it is here between
about 60 and 100 percent.

198
00:09:57.316 --> 00:10:00.756 A:middle
The next area is the utilization
across the whole system

199
00:10:00.756 --> 00:10:03.346 A:middle
because all know that our
applications do not run

200
00:10:03.346 --> 00:10:04.076 A:middle
in isolation.

201
00:10:04.466 --> 00:10:07.316 A:middle
Other applications affect
how our application runs.

202
00:10:08.326 --> 00:10:10.676 A:middle
And so here, you can see
in purple that we are using

203
00:10:10.676 --> 00:10:14.356 A:middle
about half of the total
CPU utilization potential.

204
00:10:15.386 --> 00:10:17.636 A:middle
The orange area is all
the other applications

205
00:10:18.026 --> 00:10:19.446 A:middle
which on iOS is very
well-behaved.

206
00:10:19.446 --> 00:10:21.426 A:middle
So it's a tiny little
15 percent slither.

207
00:10:22.266 --> 00:10:25.566 A:middle
And then of course, the
free area is the gray area.

208
00:10:26.366 --> 00:10:29.796 A:middle
And as we've been stressing all
week, if you have work to do,

209
00:10:30.146 --> 00:10:32.436 A:middle
you really do want to
use all the CPU can

210
00:10:32.436 --> 00:10:33.706 A:middle
and then let it go to sleep.

211
00:10:34.116 --> 00:10:38.506 A:middle
Let the computer-- the machinery
underneath your application go

212
00:10:38.506 --> 00:10:40.536 A:middle
to rest for better
performance and power.

213
00:10:42.566 --> 00:10:44.496 A:middle
Now, we have the main
section of the report.

214
00:10:45.216 --> 00:10:47.356 A:middle
This is where we have some
graph showing you with history,

215
00:10:47.506 --> 00:10:50.196 A:middle
basically, the history
of that needle up above.

216
00:10:50.286 --> 00:10:51.656 A:middle
And the first one
is a large graph

217
00:10:51.706 --> 00:10:53.296 A:middle
because that's showing
an aggregate

218
00:10:53.296 --> 00:10:56.216 A:middle
across all your threads at
the CPU utilization over time.

219
00:10:57.816 --> 00:10:59.896 A:middle
Below that, we split
it out by the threads.

220
00:11:00.726 --> 00:11:01.996 A:middle
And here, we only
