00:35:03.736 --> 00:35:08.966 A:middle
And so Quick Look is
a new powerful way

667
00:35:09.526 --> 00:35:13.456 A:middle
to debug your applications that
makes it a whole lot easier

668
00:35:13.456 --> 00:35:14.416 A:middle
and a whole lot more fun

669
00:35:14.786 --> 00:35:16.706 A:middle
to see what your
value-- the values are.

670
00:35:19.456 --> 00:35:22.446 A:middle
Visualizing data type is not the
only thing we need to visualize,

671
00:35:22.446 --> 00:35:25.506 A:middle
especially, if like me,
you work on UI things.

672
00:35:26.286 --> 00:35:29.396 A:middle
And especially, in your Mac Apps
because your windows have many,

673
00:35:29.396 --> 00:35:31.556 A:middle
many views and you
want to visualize,

674
00:35:31.556 --> 00:35:32.926 A:middle
let's say the bounce
of each view.

675
00:35:33.526 --> 00:35:37.496 A:middle
And so when I would like to
highlight is the Show View

676
00:35:37.556 --> 00:35:40.546 A:middle
Frames which will
put a colorful rec--

677
00:35:40.926 --> 00:35:44.896 A:middle
rectangle around every
view in your application.

678
00:35:45.436 --> 00:35:48.756 A:middle
I actually used this recently
because I had a toolbar

679
00:35:48.756 --> 00:35:50.336 A:middle
which I needed to make
a little bit smaller.

680
00:35:51.136 --> 00:35:52.676 A:middle
And it has-- as you know,

681
00:35:52.676 --> 00:35:56.656 A:middle
the toolbar will take the
tallest toolbar item in it

682
00:35:57.116 --> 00:35:59.196 A:middle
to represent the full height.

683
00:35:59.856 --> 00:36:02.396 A:middle
And I had one icon that
had invisible background

684
00:36:02.516 --> 00:36:04.526 A:middle
that was bigger and I didn't
know which one it was.

685
00:36:05.056 --> 00:36:07.946 A:middle
So I turn on this option and
it was easy to pinpoint exactly

686
00:36:07.946 --> 00:36:12.106 A:middle
which toolbar item it was and
I could change the, our asset,

687
00:36:12.106 --> 00:36:17.626 A:middle
debug it, make that item smaller
and fix my bug, it was green.

688
00:36:18.546 --> 00:36:23.146 A:middle
Now if you're on iOS, we also
have some solutions for you.

689
00:36:23.146 --> 00:36:27.456 A:middle
Many people don't realize
that LODB accepts expressions

690
00:36:27.456 --> 00:36:30.686 A:middle
which are fully qualified
Objective-C statements.

691
00:36:31.446 --> 00:36:33.196 A:middle
And so if you have a method,

692
00:36:33.196 --> 00:36:35.826 A:middle
let's say the UIViews
recursive description,

693
00:36:36.456 --> 00:36:39.286 A:middle
you can send a message
to that object,

694
00:36:39.556 --> 00:36:43.526 A:middle
telling it to return the string
for that recursive description

695
00:36:43.526 --> 00:36:45.796 A:middle
and print it to the console.

696
00:36:46.046 --> 00:36:48.296 A:middle
And this allows you to
see what the child views

697
00:36:48.296 --> 00:36:49.086 A:middle
of that view are.

698
00:36:49.086 --> 00:36:51.066 A:middle
And many of the properties
that you might need

699
00:36:51.066 --> 00:36:53.546 A:middle
to debug what's going
wrong with your UIViews.

700
00:36:54.186 --> 00:36:58.836 A:middle
And so these workflows
are very powerful.

701
00:36:58.836 --> 00:37:00.166 A:middle
And now I'd like to
switch gears and talk

702
00:37:00.166 --> 00:37:02.106 A:middle
about the specific
debugging workflow

703
00:37:02.106 --> 00:37:05.126 A:middle
that we've made really great
and that's XPC Services.

704
00:37:05.756 --> 00:37:10.026 A:middle
But first, let's talk a little
bit about what XPC Services are.

705
00:37:10.416 --> 00:37:13.726 A:middle
XPC Services are really
powerful bits of functionality

706
00:37:13.726 --> 00:37:15.916 A:middle
that you separate from
your main code in order

707
00:37:15.916 --> 00:37:19.066 A:middle
to have stability
or maybe security.

708
00:37:19.786 --> 00:37:22.786 A:middle
And Xcode provides a template
if you're writing a Mac App

709
00:37:22.786 --> 00:37:25.176 A:middle
that will allow you to
create one of these surfaces

710
00:37:25.586 --> 00:37:29.016 A:middle
which makes a bundle
inside your application

711
00:37:29.306 --> 00:37:31.566 A:middle
which is a separate process
that gets launched by the system

712
00:37:31.846 --> 00:37:35.426 A:middle
when you call the
APIs that call it up.

713
00:37:35.686 --> 00:37:38.556 A:middle
And this bundle can
be communicated too,

714
00:37:38.766 --> 00:37:43.546 A:middle
you can ask request things
from the bundle and when

715
00:37:43.546 --> 00:37:46.396 A:middle
that operation is completed,
it will send the message back

716
00:37:46.636 --> 00:37:49.836 A:middle
with the results
of that procedure.

717
00:37:52.786 --> 00:37:55.466 A:middle
This is possible to
do in Xcode 4 to--

718
00:37:55.466 --> 00:37:59.106 A:middle
it is possible to modify
your scheme to wait

719
00:37:59.146 --> 00:38:02.226 A:middle
for these XPC services
to come up.

720
00:38:02.226 --> 00:38:04.246 A:middle
And when they do, your
Xcode will attach to it.

721
00:38:04.766 --> 00:38:07.386 A:middle
And what does that mean
to attach to XPC Service?

722
00:38:07.386 --> 00:38:10.366 A:middle
That means it gets its own entry

723
00:38:10.366 --> 00:38:12.656 A:middle
in the debug navigator
complete with its own gauges.

724
00:38:13.326 --> 00:38:17.056 A:middle
And if you said breakpoints in
the XPC Service, they'll stop

725
00:38:17.056 --> 00:38:19.706 A:middle
in those breakpoints
just alongside your Mac

726
00:38:19.706 --> 00:38:20.746 A:middle
Application breakpoints.

727
00:38:21.166 --> 00:38:23.906 A:middle
So it's easy to be able
to step through each

728
00:38:23.906 --> 00:38:26.866 A:middle
of them concurrently just
by switching back and forth

729
00:38:26.866 --> 00:38:28.656 A:middle
between the process and
the debug navigator.

730
00:38:29.446 --> 00:38:33.046 A:middle
But the difficult part is that
when this communication ends

731
00:38:33.046 --> 00:38:35.666 A:middle
with your service, the
system is allowed to wreak

732
00:38:35.756 --> 00:38:39.286 A:middle
that XPC Service to free up
system resources for other apps.

733
00:38:39.766 --> 00:38:43.566 A:middle
And so to make that even better,

734
00:38:43.916 --> 00:38:46.156 A:middle
we've improved the
situation in Xcode 5.

735
00:38:47.156 --> 00:38:50.026 A:middle
When Xcode debugs your
application, it starts listening

736
00:38:50.256 --> 00:38:52.286 A:middle
for any services in
your application bundle.

737
00:38:53.906 --> 00:38:57.676 A:middle
And when those services come
up, Xcode automatically attaches

738
00:38:57.676 --> 00:38:59.716 A:middle
to it, meaning, you can set
breakpoints, you can see it

739
00:38:59.716 --> 00:39:02.106 A:middle
in the debug navigator,
you can check out the CPU

740
00:39:02.106 --> 00:39:04.236 A:middle
and memory reports for those.

741
00:39:04.916 --> 00:39:07.856 A:middle
And when it goes away, Xcode
automatically detaches.

742
00:39:08.496 --> 00:39:12.836 A:middle
But Xcode is waiting once again
for that service to come back

743
00:39:13.366 --> 00:39:16.716 A:middle
and we'll attach to it again,
providing a seamless experience

744
00:39:16.756 --> 00:39:18.616 A:middle
for you XPC Service debugging.

745
00:39:22.336 --> 00:39:24.146 A:middle
This works great
in practice and I'd

746
00:39:24.146 --> 00:39:25.496 A:middle
like to invite Christopher
Friesen

747
00:39:25.496 --> 00:39:27.626 A:middle
up one more time to
give a final demo.

748
00:39:28.686 --> 00:39:31.116 A:middle
&gt;&gt; So yet again our users
want another feature.

749
00:39:31.116 --> 00:39:34.526 A:middle
They want to be able to look
at any image of the internet.

750
00:39:35.926 --> 00:39:38.326 A:middle
Now this might be kind
of dangerous to do.

751
00:39:38.326 --> 00:39:41.406 A:middle
So we're going to put this
functionality in an XPC Service

752
00:39:41.406 --> 00:39:43.766 A:middle
so that it's partition
from our main application.

753
00:39:44.116 --> 00:39:46.906 A:middle
So we've changed the
input to be a URL

754
00:39:47.446 --> 00:39:49.126 A:middle
and we put this on our service.

755
00:39:49.416 --> 00:39:51.386 A:middle
So let's take a look
and see what Xcode does

756
00:39:51.386 --> 00:39:52.856 A:middle
as we debug this application.

757
00:39:58.476 --> 00:40:00.976 A:middle
So I'll click the run here,
our application starting up.

758
00:40:01.176 --> 00:40:05.426 A:middle
Now we've hit a breakpoint where
the main app is now setting

759
00:40:05.426 --> 00:40:07.836 A:middle
up an XPC connection
to talk to our service.

760
00:40:09.526 --> 00:40:11.476 A:middle
You'll notice that in
the debug navigator,

761
00:40:11.916 --> 00:40:14.176 A:middle
we currently have just
a single application.

762
00:40:14.656 --> 00:40:17.396 A:middle
Our debug gauges and
threads and stacks.

763
00:40:19.176 --> 00:40:23.566 A:middle
Now as I continue, watch
this area and you'll see

764
00:40:23.566 --> 00:40:25.816 A:middle
that we automatically
attached to the XPC process.

765
00:40:26.366 --> 00:40:31.006 A:middle
And there it just showed up.

766
00:40:32.376 --> 00:40:33.936 A:middle
You'll note that it
has a different icon

767
00:40:33.936 --> 00:40:34.946 A:middle
in your main application.

768
00:40:35.086 --> 00:40:36.996 A:middle
It's a black and white
screwdriver and a wrench.

769
00:40:37.586 --> 00:40:39.866 A:middle
And again, it has
the same debug gauges

770
00:40:40.136 --> 00:40:43.646 A:middle
and the same capabilities
in this debug area.

771
00:40:44.246 --> 00:40:48.946 A:middle
As you see in our application,
we've fetched the image

772
00:40:48.946 --> 00:40:50.546 A:middle
and we're displaying it.

773
00:40:52.276 --> 00:40:57.566 A:middle
Now in order to debug in your
XPC Service, you simply need

774
00:40:57.566 --> 00:40:58.696 A:middle
to go set your breakpoints.

775
00:41:00.076 --> 00:41:02.316 A:middle
So we'll go to our breakpoint
that we've already created.

776
00:41:02.916 --> 00:41:05.366 A:middle
I'll set it in our service
and then I'll go back

777
00:41:05.366 --> 00:41:06.896 A:middle
and exercise our application.

778
00:41:07.476 --> 00:41:10.656 A:middle
Here we are.

779
00:41:11.436 --> 00:41:12.776 A:middle
It's now in the debug navigator,

780
00:41:12.776 --> 00:41:15.146 A:middle
you can see that we've
got our main application

781
00:41:15.146 --> 00:41:19.326 A:middle
which is still running, the
gauges are still whirling away,

782
00:41:19.326 --> 00:41:24.126 A:middle
the UI is still responsive, but
the XPC Service has been paused.

783
00:41:25.646 --> 00:41:27.196 A:middle
And here you see
that we're stopped

784
00:41:27.196 --> 00:41:29.636 A:middle
in thread 16 on stack
frame zero.

785
00:41:34.076 --> 00:41:35.986 A:middle
And we can continue
our application.

786
00:41:36.656 --> 00:41:40.396 A:middle
And we see that we've
returned back from the service,

787
00:41:40.396 --> 00:41:45.276 A:middle
applied the filter and
display it in the UI.

788
00:41:45.426 --> 00:41:46.726 A:middle
Now another thing to note is

789
00:41:47.216 --> 00:41:48.546 A:middle
that the Stop button
doesn't show

790
00:41:48.546 --> 00:41:50.006 A:middle
that multiple processes
are running.

791
00:41:51.396 --> 00:41:53.196 A:middle
This is because we
grouped them together

792
00:41:54.836 --> 00:41:57.876 A:middle
so that whenever you click stop,
we'll stop your main application

793
00:41:58.186 --> 00:42:01.136 A:middle
as well as your-- any XPC
processes that you have running,

794
00:42:01.136 --> 00:42:05.206 A:middle
this is so that you can go
back, change your source code

795
00:42:05.206 --> 00:42:07.916 A:middle
and then next time you
run, we'll use that--

796
00:42:07.916 --> 00:42:10.596 A:middle
those changes in
your XPC Services.

797
00:42:11.906 --> 00:42:16.326 A:middle
So let's watch that debug
area as I click Stop.

798
00:42:16.476 --> 00:42:19.396 A:middle
I know, it's exciting
when it just works.

799
